<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-cant-login-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Can&rsquo;t log in,&rdquo; plainly &mdash; and whose job it is.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>When you can&rsquo;t log in to QuickBooks, the wall you&rsquo;ve hit is almost always the <em>Intuit account</em> that sits in front of the software &mdash; the same account that holds your password, your User ID, your two-factor setup, and your subscription. So &ldquo;can&rsquo;t log in&rdquo; usually means one of a few things: the password or User ID is wrong; a two-factor verification code isn&rsquo;t arriving; the account is locked after too many failed attempts; the email you&rsquo;re using isn&rsquo;t the one tied to the subscription; a browser cache or extension is blocking sign-in to QuickBooks Online; or Intuit itself is having an outage.</p>
      <p>Here is the honest part, stated plainly: <strong>every one of those is Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve, not ours.</strong> An independent firm has no back door to your Intuit account &mdash; we cannot reset your password, retrieve your User ID, deliver a two-factor code, or unlock you. The legitimate path is Intuit&rsquo;s own recovery and support, and the steps below point you there. Where an independent ProAdvisor <em>can</em> help is strictly after you&rsquo;re back in: if the lockout left the books behind, miscategorized, or you&rsquo;re unsure which company file is the right one, that bookkeeping work &mdash; the books, never the login &mdash; is our lane.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

